WISCONSIN SOCCER COACHES ASSOCIATION POLL
Through Sept. 28
Division 1: 1. Milw. Marquette; 2. Arrowhead; 3. Mukwonago; 4. Beloit Memorial; 5. Hudson. Honorable mention: Sun Prairie, Madison Memorial, Eau Claire Memorial, Kimberly, Green Bay Preble, Appleton North, Brookfield Central, Oconomowoc, Middleton, Madison West.
Division 2: 1. Whitefish Bay; 2. Cedarburg; 3. Brookfield East; 4. Waunakee; 5. Pewaukee. Honorable mention: Green Bay East, Onalaska, Wauwatosa East, Oregon, Elkhorn.
Division 3: 1. Delavan-Darien; 2. Grafton; 3. Appleton Xavier; 4. Catholic Memorial; 5. Green Bay Notre Dame. Honorable mention: Freedom, Winneconne, Mount Horeb, Whitnall, New Holstein.
Division 4: 1. University School; 2. Sturgeon Bay; 3. Lake Country Lutheran; 4. Sheboygan County Christian; 5. Columbus Catholic. Honorable mention: Brookfield Academy, Racine Prairie, Barron.
NOTABLE TEAM OF THE WEEK: Brookfield Academy . The Division 4 side upended Catholic Memorial — ranked fourth in the Division 3 state poll — 3-2 last Friday. Before that, the Blue Knights beat Heritage Christian, 10-1. Nathan Washburn had two goals and three assists in that Midwest Classic match.
PLAYER OF THE WEEK: Nate Sampson, University School . The junior forward scored six goals in two matches as the Wildcats stretched their record to 9-0 this season. Sampson put three in the net in a 10-0 win over Midwest Classic Conference rival Kenosha Christian Life, then scored another hat trick in a 4-1 win over St. Anthony. University School is No. 1 in Division 4 state poll.
LOOKING GOOD: A school better known for football is finding success in soccer this season.
Mukwonago is ranked third among Division 1 teams in the state coaches' poll, and ninth in the National Soccer Coaches Association of America regional poll released Sept. 22.
The Indians are tied for first in the tough Classic 8 with a 3-0-1 mark.
So far the team has navigated a tricky schedule, going 3-0-2 against five quality teams: Mukwonago beat Catholic Memorial (3-2), drew with Arrowhead (1-1), beat Madison West (3-1), defeated Woodland leader Greendale (2-1) and drew with Little Ten leader Oconomowoc (0-0).
The Indians finished 2-5 in league play last season, but this year the team's young players have matured, said coach Nate Johnson. "We were extremely young last year, and hopefully our strategy to pull up younger players pays off this year," Johnson said at the beginning of the season. The team has nine of 11 starters back, including the entire defensive back line.
KICKED OUT: A Metro Classic Conference match between Racine St. Catherine's and Martin Luther last week finished a bit short-handed. In the 10th minute of the match, the head referee dismissed one of the assistant referees for poor performance, said St. Catherine's coach Ben Lake. The remaining two officials conferred with the two coaches after the dismissal and resumed play, with the two referees officiating the rest of the match. The Angels defeated the Spartans, 10-0. "I have never seen anything like it," Lake said.
TOUGH TOURNEY: Milwaukee Marquette suffered its second loss to an out-of-state side last week, falling to Rockhurst, Mo., 2-0, in the annual Jesuit Classic at Quad Park. Earlier this season the Hilltoppers lost TO Chaminade College Prep of St. Louis. Marquette regrouped the next day and defeated Gonzaga of Washington, D.C., 5-2. Rockhurst beat Regis, Colo., 1-0, on Saturday to finish the four-team tournament, 2-0.
TABLE TOPS: Sides are in the stretch run to reach the top of league tables, with several big matches this week that will help decide conference championships. Milwaukee Marquette and Brookfield East are both undefeated (4-0) in Greater Metro matches, and play each other at 7 p.m. Tuesday at East. The Hilltoppers are the defending league champs. In the Midwest Classic, Lake Country Lutheran and University School, both 4-0 in conference matches, meet 4:30 p.m. Wednesday at University School. In the Woodland, Greendale and Whitnall, both 4-1 in league play, play 6:30 p.m. Wednesday at Greendale.
POLLING PLACES: Milwaukee Marquette was 15th in the national Fab 50 compiled by Top Drawer Soccer. The Hilltoppers are No. 1 in the TDS state rankings, with Cedarburg second and Whitefish Bay third.
Marquette also tops the National Soccer Coaches Association of America regional poll, with Arrowhead fourth, Whitefish Bay fifth, Sheboygan North ninth and Mukwonago tenth.
COMING UP Kettle Moraine at Arrowhead, 6:30 p.m. Tuesday: State-ranked Arrowhead tries to stay atop the Classic 8.
Waukesha West at Catholic Memorial, 6:30 p.m. Tuesday at Waukesha South: Both teams are 3-1 in Classic 8 matches and look to stay in the hunt for a conference crown.
Arrowhead at Brookfield East, 7:30 p.m. Thursday: The Warhawks, ranked No. 2 in Division 1 state poll, take on the Spartans, ranked No. 3 in Division 2 poll in a non-conference match.
Mike Dillet Memorial Tournament, Friday and Saturday: New Berlin West hosts eight-team event to honor former coach who passed away in 2009. Field includes Hartford, Oak Creek and Kenosha Indian Trail.
